	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-1528 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-after-deadline tag-grammar" id="post-1528">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Tangled Passages</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Philip B. Corbett			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-07-21T12:00:33+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 21, 2015 8:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 21, 2015 8:00 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//afterdeadline.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/21/tangled-passages-11/" data-title="Tangled Passages" data-description="The period can be a reader&#039;s best friend. We should use them more often.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The period can be a reader&#8217;s best friend. We should use it more often.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Writers often try to wedge news developments, details, background and broad significance all into one sentence, especially in leads. We seem terrified that a period provides an escape hatch and readers will flee. But I think it&#8217;s more likely that long, dense, winding sentences will drive them away; clear and digestible ones will keep them reading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here are some recent examples where we could have done better. Most of these passages aren&#8217;t terrible; the grammar is largely sound and a careful reader can find the way through. But each sentence would be better split up or pared down.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>BRUSSELS &mdash; Haggling through the night into Monday morning over a deal to calm Greece&#8217;s debt crisis, European leaders demanded that Athens make new concessions and quickly adopt a host of economic policy changes as they worked to overcome deep divisions and avert a historic fracture in the Continent&#8217;s common currency.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>As testy talks dragged on past the self-imposed midnight deadline they had set without an agreement, leaders of the 19 countries that use the euro struggled to draft a compromise that would assuage some of Greece&#8217;s concerns over tough German-set terms while assuring creditors that a new bailout worth tens of billions of euros would not be money wasted.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The mood grew increasingly tense as it became clear that the leaders were weighing steps that Greece&#8217;s left-wing government, while desperate for a deal to pave the way for new funding, would find difficult to sell at home &mdash; just a week after Greek voters overwhelmingly rejected softer terms in a referendum.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One long, complex sentence is a challenge. But three in a row, each over 50 words and packed with multiple clauses and ideas, may create an insuperable obstacle. Break them up. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>LOS ANGELES &mdash; With San Francisco&#8217;s immigration policies drawing criticism from Democrats and Republicans alike, Mayor Edwin M. Lee said Wednesday that he would speak to federal officials about how the city could participate in a new Obama administration deportation program, after a Mexican felon who had been deported five times was charged with murdering a 32-year-old woman, Kathryn Steinle, as she walked on a tourist pier in the city last week.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This winding, 72-word sentence sandwiches the news between two background clauses, with far too many details that could have been saved for later.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>While Katonah has had a small CVS outlet at the center since late last year, hundreds of residents objected to efforts to open a larger one, arguing that the new CVS, which would stock groceries and cosmetics as well as pharmaceuticals, would harm small merchants on the main street and open the door to a spate of chain stores that would ruin the hamlet&#8217;s quirky, small town character.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This sentence, nearly 70 words, contains a succession of digressions. Simplify.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>While Mr. Walker is well positioned to compete in the first-in-the-nation caucuses in Iowa, which he considers a must-win state, he has lost momentum in those other three states because of long absences, relatively modest political operations or increasingly hard-line positions that appear intended for Iowa conservatives.</em> &hellip;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In other remarks, including his speech here, Mr. Walker described himself as a former Boy Scout and son of the heartland who would defend the &#8220;unborn,&#8221; the Americans who oppose same-sex marriage on religious grounds, and more broadly the conservative and traditional citizens who feel under attack from what they consider coastal elites.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some long sentences are still easy to navigate because they include a series or list that is linear and straightforward. But in these two sentences, the elements in the series are themselves complex or not parallel, making for rough going.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>VIENNA &mdash; For more than a decade, the C.I.A. has closely followed the workings of one Iranian officer and his sprawling nuclear empire: Mohsen Fakhrizadeh, the relentless driving force behind what Western intelligence agencies say was Iran&#8217;s Manhattan Project, its effort to design a compact nuclear weapon that could fit atop a missile.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Now, in the final push for a comprehensive nuclear agreement with Iran, accounting for the accomplishments of Mr. Fakhrizadeh and his team of university scientists, missile engineers and military officers is emerging as one of the last and most formidable obstacles &mdash; perhaps on a par with the question of whether inspectors will be able, on short notice, to step into any place they suspect might conceal bomb-related work.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The chief of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Yukiya Amano, is flying into Tehran on Thursday to meet with President Hassan Rouhani and Iran&#8217;s top national security officials in the latest effort to agree on a plan for interviewing scientists, examining their documents and visiting a long list of places where the agency believes they conducted nuclear-related experiments.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Once again we have three successive sentences that are long, complex and overstuffed. Readers will be too exhausted to go on.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>CAIRO &mdash; The Islamic State group claimed responsibility for a powerful explosion outside the Italian Consulate&#8217;s compound in downtown Cairo early Saturday that killed one person and was the first major bombing of a foreign diplomatic mission since the start of an insurgency here nearly two years ago.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here, the news (&#8220;killed one person&#8221;) and the broader context (&#8220;was the first major bombing &hellip;&#8221;) are awkwardly and jarringly yoked together. Simply putting a period after &#8220;person&#8221; and doing the rest as a separate sentence would be much smoother and easier to digest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Federal prosecutors on Wednesday said they had begun an investigation into possible collusion among the airlines to limit seating, two years after the Justice Department approved the latest in a wave of airline mergers, saying the combination would benefit consumers.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Appending the two-year-old background to the lead sentence makes it hard to digest; break it up.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the other hand, this Page One top also offers news, background and analysis, on a complex topic. But it&#8217;s easy to follow, because the elements are introduced in a series of clear, lucid sentences, not all stuffed into one.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>SHANGHAI &mdash; As the Chinese stock market slumps, the country&#8217;s government has stepped in boldly, unveiling a series of measures to prop up shares. But those efforts have done little to stabilize the market, with stocks continuing to slide on Wednesday.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The losses create a political and economic challenge for the nation&#8217;s leadership.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Beijing could face social unrest if the sell-off accelerates, since tens of millions of ordinary investors have plowed their savings into the market. The psychological toll on investors, in turn, could erode consumer confidence, dragging down growth in the already slowing economy.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;<br />
<strong>In a Word</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week&#8217;s grab bag of grammar, style and other missteps, compiled with help from colleagues and readers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The most devastating chapter began around 2:30 a.m. on June 25, the authorities said, when residents of Elizabeth reported hearing gunfire and seeing a body <strong>laying</strong> at the intersection of New Point Road and Seventh Street, the authorities said.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;lying,&#8221; not &#8220;laying.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>A new app called Wag! can bring on-demand relief to dogs and their busy owners. <strong>Think Uber</strong> for dog walkers.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We should resist this overused &#8220;Think [blank]&#8221; construction, as well as the already tired comparison of everything to Uber.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Today the tunnels barely manage <strong>24 trains</strong> at peak hours. Closing one for long-term repairs, experts say, will reduce the hourly number to <strong>six trains</strong>, an <strong>80 percent</strong> drop, which, as Tom Wright, president of the Regional Plan Association, put it the other day, would be &#8220;a catastrophe for the Northeast,&#8221; with implications that &#8220;register on&#8221; the national gross domestic product.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Eighteen is three-fourths of 24, so unless some information is missing here, this would be a 75 percent drop.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Op-Ed] The bottom line is that <strong>none</strong> of the critics of an Iran deal, from <strong>Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu</strong> to all the harrumphing Republican presidential hopefuls, <strong>has</strong> offered a single credible alternative that accomplishes even what has been achieved since 2013.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In our style, &#8220;Israeli&#8221; should not be part of the title before the name. Also, &#8220;none&#8221; in a case like this should be construed as plural. The Times&#8217;s stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>none</strong>. Despite a widespread assumption that it stands for <em>not one</em>, the word has been construed as a plural (<em>not any</em>) in most contexts for centuries. H. W. Fowler&#8217;s Dictionary of Modern English Usage (1926) endorsed the plural use. Make <em>none</em> plural except when emphasizing the idea of <em>not one</em> or <em>no one</em> &mdash; and then consider using those phrases instead.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>He associates this clichÃ©d suburban idyll with what he calls &#8220;the Dream&#8221; &mdash; not the American dream of opportunity and a better life for one&#8217;s children; not Martin Luther King Jr.&#8217;s dream of freedom and equality (which <strong>the Reverend King</strong> observed was &#8220;a dream deeply rooted in the American dream&#8221;), but instead, in Mr. Coates&#8217;s somewhat confusing use of the term, an exclusionary white dream rooted in a history of subjugation and privilege.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is not our style for the use of &#8220;Reverend.&#8221; Here&#8217;s the stylebook entry:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Rev.</strong> <em>The Rev. Lee A. Bildots</em>. For most Protestants the later reference is <em>Mr., Ms., Mrs.</em> or <em>Miss</em>. For Roman Catholics, Orthodox Christians and those Episcopalians who prefer it, use <em>Father</em> in later references: <em>Father Bildots</em>. Lutheran ministers, in later references, are normally called <em>Pastor</em>: <em>Pastor Bildots</em>. (For an exception, see pastor.) Never use <em>the Rev.</em> (or just <em>Reverend</em>) with a surname alone, as in <em>Reverend Bildots is coming to dinner</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Picture caption] Mr. King and Ms. White after she <strong>graduated law school</strong> at St. John&#8217;s University in 2001.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;graduated from &hellip; &#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>South Carolina, the first state to secede from the Union and one that has quarreled often, in the ensuing years, over matters the Civil War never quite settled, <strong>dispatched with</strong> at least one of those issues on Thursday as Gov. Nikki R. Haley signed into law a bill to remove the Confederate battle flag from the grounds of the State House.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Dispatch&#8221; is a transitive verb and should be used with a direct object, not with &#8220;with.&#8221; Make it &#8220;dispatched at least one of those issues,&#8221; or else &#8220;dispensed with at least one of those issues.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>Owned by Eric Bernstein</strong> &mdash; a planner and technical director for New York events &mdash; <strong>the loft&#8217;s rent</strong> is reduced for Ms. Schefman and Ms. Petkoski.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dangler. The rent is not owned by Eric Bernstein.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>He had asked another old friend, Edul Ahmad, to <strong>loan</strong> him money to help pay back some of the funds.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stylebook wants &#8220;lend,&#8221; not &#8220;loan,&#8221; as the verb.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The Knicks are trying <strong>to make a wholesale rebuild</strong> in the wake of a 17-win season, and Porzingis, a 19-year-old forward, is central to their plans.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let&#8217;s avoid the sports-jargon use of &#8220;rebuild&#8221; as a noun. And in any case, you wouldn&#8217;t &#8220;make&#8221; a rebuild (or a rebuilding).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Instead, he roamed the globe <strong>advocating for human rights</strong> and battling diseases from malaria to blinding trachoma.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it something like &#8220;campaigning for human rights.&#8221; As the stylebook notes, the verb &#8220;advocate&#8221; should take a direct object.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>More affluent minorities have diversified many predominantly white neighborhoods in those cities, but the segregation of <strong>less-wealthy</strong> minority families remains entrenched.</em> &hellip; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The changes also could prompt some governments to follow the example of Westchester County, which has <strong>foregone</strong> some federal funding because of its refusal to comply with <strong>fair housing</strong> regulations.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No hyphen is wanted in &#8220;less wealthy,&#8221; though we could probably use one in &#8220;fair-housing regulations.&#8221; And the word we wanted is &#8220;forgone,&#8221; not &#8220;foregone.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>As the cameras and news media crews <strong>amassed</strong> before her, it was clear that Tuesday was not the best of days for Susannah Mushatt Jones.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Amassed is a transitive verb, as in, &#8220;He amassed a fortune.&#8221; Here, it could be, &#8220;As the cameras and news media crews massed before her.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The ruling blocked efforts by the company to subpoena documents that might have <strong>proven</strong> the identity of the condo&#8217;s beneficial owner.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stylebook prefers &#8220;proved&#8221; for the verb.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Green or dark brown <strong>overall</strong>, this native leech has orange spots with a lighter belly.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As an adverb, make &#8220;over all&#8221; two words.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>They described the delegates as significant, including some Taliban officials who had gone to the previous, <strong>less-formal</strong> talks.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hyphens are generally not needed in comparative or superlative modifiers with more/most or less/least.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>On Saturday, Mr. Bush, whose wife is Mexican, said he took offense <strong>to</strong> Mr. Trump&#8217;s comments.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You take offense &#8220;at&#8221; something, not &#8220;to.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Three years ago, the mayor here did something that surprised everyone, including himself: He apologized for the killings, becoming <strong>one of the only Indonesian officials</strong> to do so and, historians say, the first to do it officially, on behalf of his government.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;One of the only&#8221; is colloquial and illogical. Make it &#8220;one of the few.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mr. Jacobs, the boyish-looking 38-year-old chairman of the organ department at the Juilliard School and a well-traveled concert performer in his own right, was giving a private tour of some of New York&#8217;s finest organs, including those of the Church of St. Ignatius Loyola on Park Avenue and the Church of St. Mary the Virgin, near Times Square. (St. Patrick&#8217;s and St. Ignatius are Roman Catholic, St. Mary <strong>Episcopalian</strong>.)</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>episcopal</strong>. Capitalize the adjective in references to the Episcopal Church and its members and clergy: <em>an Episcopal minister</em>. Use <em>Episcopalian(s)</em> for its members, as a noun only. The lowercase term <em>episcopal</em> refers in general to bishops, of any faith: <em>episcopal rank</em>, etc. For that meaning, it is often clearer to rephrase: <em>A meeting of bishops</em>, etc.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Such were the circumstances that moved DeAndre Jordan, a shot-blocking, volume-rebounding center, to re-sign with the Los Angeles Clippers early Thursday morning despite last week&#8217;s <strong>verbal deal</strong> with Mark Cuban&#8217;s Dallas Mavericks.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And here&#8217;s the stylebook again:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â<strong>oral, verbal</strong>. Use oral to mean spoken. Verbal applies to spoken or written words.â</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Web summary] Francis <strong>gave</strong> the first Mass of his Latin American Trip in Guayaquil, where hundreds of thousands heard him speak.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And again:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>âMass</strong> (religious). Capitalize this and other formally named prayer services: <em>Divine Liturgy</em>; <em>the Eucharist</em>; <em>the Divine Eucharist</em>; <em>Friday Prayer</em> (Islam). But: <em>funeral Mass</em>; <em>high Mass</em>; <em>low Mass</em>; <em>nuptial Mass</em>; <em>requiem Mass</em>. High Mass is <em>sung</em>; low Mass is <em>said</em>. Masses are not held and do not take place; they may be <em>offered</em>, <em>celebrated</em>, <em>said</em> or <em>sung</em>.â</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>When his sister graduated from college, Mr. Walker <strong>gifted</strong> her about 4,000 hours of live music, including Phish and the Dead, on tape &mdash; &#8220;a significant portion of my analog collection,&#8221; he said.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ugh. How about &#8220;gave&#8221;?</p>
	</div>
